## 7. Required Metadata Schema

Every controlled asset must include the following minimum metadata.

| Field | Required | Description |
|---|---|---|
| Asset Code | Yes | official classification code |
| Asset Title | Yes | human-readable title |
| Version | Yes | semantic version |
| Status | Yes | lifecycle state |
| Owner | Yes | responsible role or authority |
| Library Family | Yes | Layer 1 value |
| Domain Class | Yes | Layer 2 value |
| Collection Class | Yes | Layer 3 value |
| Artifact Type | Yes | Layer 4 value |
| Sequence ID | Yes | numeric identifier |
| Use Case | Yes | intended business or learner use |
| Audience | Yes | target user or buyer |
| Dependencies | Conditional | prerequisite files, scripts, or linked assets |
| Parent Asset | Conditional | parent code if asset belongs to larger package |
| Release Date | Conditional | required for released assets |
| Review Date | Conditional | required for approved or released assets |
| Tags | Recommended | search and filter terms |
| Storage Path | Yes | canonical folder or repository path |

### 7.1 Extended Metadata Recommended for Product Assets

For customer-facing assets, also include:

- difficulty level
- output type
- platform compatibility
- monetization class
- delivery format
- license scope
- validation status
- packaging completeness

