## 9. Naming Standard

The human-readable file name should follow this pattern:

`[AssetCode]_[Short-Title]`

### 9.1 File Naming Rules

- Use title case or structured hyphen style consistently.
- Keep short titles concise and operational.
- Do not use vague names such as `final`, `new`, `latest`, `good copy`, or `updated version`.
- Do not omit the asset code from controlled deliverables.
- Do not place status words in the short title if status is already tracked in metadata.

### 9.2 Good Examples

- `LIB-SLS-CLUSTER-MANUAL-001-v1.0.0_Sales-Funnel-Architecture-Manual.pdf`
- `CERT-EDU-MODULE-WORKSHEET-004-v1.0.0_Module-04-Worksheet.md`
- `GOV-COM-INDEX-POLICY-002-v1.0.0_Library-Naming-Policy.pdf`

### 9.3 Invalid Examples

- `sales manual final.pdf`
- `new prompt list.md`
- `cluster update latest version 2.pdf`

---

## 10. Folder and Repository Placement Standard

Classification must map to storage structure. The default folder pattern is:

`/Family/Domain/Collection/Type/AssetCode/`

### 10.1 Example Paths

- `/LIB/SLS/CLUSTER/MANUAL/LIB-SLS-CLUSTER-MANUAL-001-v1.0.0/`
- `/CERT/EDU/MODULE/WORKSHEET/CERT-EDU-MODULE-WORKSHEET-004-v1.0.0/`
- `/GOV/COM/INDEX/POLICY/GOV-COM-INDEX-POLICY-002-v1.0.0/`

### 10.2 Standard Contents for an Asset Folder

A released asset folder should contain, where applicable:

- source file
- PDF release
- markdown or editable source
- README
- metadata record
- related assets
- changelog reference
- license file
- support materials or placeholders

