## 18. Implementation Standard

### 18.1 Required Operational Controls

- master library index
- controlled naming pattern
- sequence issuance log
- approved class list
- version history mechanism
- archive policy
- periodic metadata audit

### 18.2 Recommended Automation Targets

The classification system should be automated wherever possible. Recommended automation points:

- code generation from metadata form inputs
- folder creation from class selection
- validation of required metadata fields
- duplicate code detection
- lifecycle status dashboard
- release package completeness checks
- tag normalization
- deprecated-to-superseded link tracking

---

## 19. Audit Checklist

Use this checklist before classifying an asset as released.

- asset has one primary classification
- asset code matches metadata
- domain reflects primary operational use
- collection class is correct
- artifact type is correct
- sequence is unique
- version is valid
- lifecycle state is declared
- storage path is canonical
- index entry exists
- release package is complete
- parent-child links are recorded when applicable

---

## 20. Change Control

Changes to this manual require governance review when they affect:

- class definitions
- metadata requirements
- syntax rules
- lifecycle definitions
- repository placement rules
- packaging rules
- automation dependencies
- certification mapping

Minor wording corrections may be issued as patch revisions if no classification logic changes.

---

## 21. Final Rule

If an asset cannot be classified cleanly, it is not ready for release.

The purpose of classification is not labeling for its own sake. The purpose is operational control. A controlled library is one in which every asset can be identified, located, interpreted, versioned, governed, and reused without ambiguity.

